<HL>
   Japanese Production
   Of Motor Vehicles
   Rose 8.1% in August
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN TOYOY NSANY J.MOT J.MZD
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Japan's output of cars, trucks and buses grew
8.1% in August from a year earlier to 962,257 units on strong
domestic demand, the Japan Automobile Manufacturers'
Association said.
   The total was a record for August, surpassing the high of
890,339 units set a year earlier. Output in July was up 10%
to 1,211,000 units.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Domestic sales rose 14% in August from a year earlier to
478,588 units, breaking the record for the month of 421,493
set in August 1989. Export data weren't yet complete, but
association officials said they expect them to show a drop of
about 1% from year-earlier levels.
   The vigorous domestic demand reflected sustained economic
growth fueled by healthy personal spending, among other
things, the officials said. Japan's economy now has been
expanding for 46 months in a row. That's its second longest
postwar stretch of growth, after the 57-month skein from
October 1965 to July 1970.
   In August, production of passenger cars climbed 12% from a
year earlier to 709,785, also a record for the month.
Medium-sized cars showed a 19% rise to 138,498, while small
cars registered a 6.1% gain at 507,845. Production of
minicars surged 64% to 63,442.
   Truck output slid 1.7% to 249,436. Medium-sized trucks
registered a 3.4% drop at 89,394, while small trucks had a
6.2% gain to 88,568. Output of minitrucks dropped 7.9% to
71,474. Bus production climbed 12% to 3,036.
   By maker, Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's biggest car
manufacturer, reported production of 292,780 units, up 18%
from a year earlier. Nissan Motor Co., the second largest,
produced 168,929 cars, trucks and buses, a drop of 1.3%.
Mitsubishi Motors Corp. made 7.8% more motor vehicles than in
the year-earlier month, or 98,008 units. Production by Mazda
Motor Corp. rose 8.9% to 101,950.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0160
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0160.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Winners, Losers Take Stock of Glass-Steagall Battle
   ---
   Banks Bask in Equity-Underwriting Victory;
   But New Role May Prove Symbolic for Now
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   JPM BT CCI CMB T.CM T.RY
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
SECURITIES (SCR)
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Banks may have won their battle for power to
underwrite corporate-stock issues, but it could be years
before stock underwriting does much to bolster their bottom
lines.
   The Federal Reserve Board's decision to grant
equity-underwriting power to J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. last week
broke down the final barrier for banks anxious to compete
head-on with Wall Street in providing financial services to
corporate America. An underwriter buys an issue of stocks or
bonds from a corporation that wants to raise money, then
resells the securities to investors, hopefully at a profit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But with the stock-underwriting business at a low ebb,
analysts figure the banks' new powers are more symbolic than
real, at least for now.
   "It's an important strategic issue in the long term, but
anybody who anticipates a huge windfall in the near term is
deluded," said James McDermott, director of research at
Keefe, Bruyette &amp; Woods. "The equity markets are under
pressure, the competition is severe and profit margins are
falling."
   Bankers, though pleased that the Fed has seen fit to grant
powers denied banks since the Depression by the 1933
Glass-Steagall Act, concede that their new status isn't a
make-or-break issue.
   Bankers say stock underwriting will be one more service
among many that banks can provide to corporate clients. They
doubt that many banks, if any, will spend heavily over the
next few years to build the equity sales, trading and
research staffs that would enable them to compete
head-to-head in stock underwriting with big Wall Street
investment banks such as Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. or Goldman,
Sachs &amp; Co.
   Instead, it appears more likely that any stock
underwriting by banks would be done as part of financing
packages that banks arrange for their corporate clients, and
which could also include bank loans and debt securities.
Right now, if raising funds through some form of stock issue
is part of a financing package, banks have to seek help from
securities dealers.
   Banks would prefer to collect profits not only from
arranging complex financings, but also from selling the
securities involved to investors. "With underwriting power,
we get all the profits," said one banker.
   The banks' new stock-underwriting powers come with
restrictions. For one thing, banks will have to segregate
their underwriting business from their banking business.
Federal officials are particularly anxious to avoid any
perception that federal desposit insurance protects risky
stock trading and underwriting activities. This means
duplicate staffs and limits on information-sharing among a
bank's lending and securities officers, and that will impede
banks from realizing the full potential of underwriting
powers.
   What's more, for the moment at least, the Fed is
restricting the amount of underwriting business a bank can
do, whether it involves corporate bonds or stocks, to 10% of
gross revenue of the bank's securities subsidiary. Bankers
complain that the 10% limit puts a crimp in their ability to
compete with Wall Street firms.
   But Robert Tortoriello, an attorney specializing in
Glass-Steagall issues, said J.P. Morgan generates large
revenue in its securities subsidiary through its activities
as a major government bond dealer. This leaves Morgan plenty
of leeway to underwrite stocks within the 10% limit, he said.
   In any event, nobody expects community banks, or even many
of the big regional banks, to ever use the new
stock-underwriting powers. Indeed, some analysts suspect that
the Federal Reserve, deeply concerned about the health of the
nation's banks, will severely limit the number of banks it
authorizes to underwrite stock offerings.
   "By approving Morgan first, which has a very strong
capital base, the Fed is sending a message that there's a
strong bias in favor of capital-strong institutions" in the
Fed's decision to award expanded banking powers, said Keefe
Bruyette's Mr. McDermott.
   Despite its lengthy and aggressive effort to win
stock-underwriting authority, J.P. Morgan officials refused
to discuss their strategy or objectives for underwriting
corporate-stock issues. "We don't want to overplay it," said
a spokesman.
   Other banks seeking stock-underwriting powers are Bankers
Trust Co., Citicorp, Chase Manhattan Bank, Royal Bank of
Canada and Canadian Imperial Bank.
   (See related story: "Securities Industry Has Little
Leverage" -- WSJ Sept. 24, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0159
</DOCNO>
