<HL>
   International:
   Groupe Michelin Posts
   Loss for First Half
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   F.MIC
</CO>
<IN>
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- Groupe Michelin surprised analysts by posting a
larger-than-expected loss for this year's first half.
   Michelin, which became the world's biggest tire company
when it acquired Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co. this year, posted
a first-half loss of 363 million francs ($68.7 million), and
warned that the second half is looking even worse. It said a
loss is likely for the full year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Michelin said first-half sales declined 4.4% to 27.22
billion francs. It blamed the decline on currency
fluctuations.
   The loss compares to a 1.46 billion-franc profit in 1989's
first half, and a 2.45 billion-franc profit for all of 1989.
Michelin said it is making a large effort to return to
profitability in 1991.
   As with other tire makers, it blamed the loss on heavy
price competition, on sluggish auto sales in both the U.S.
and Europe, on rising costs and on a plan announced in June
to cut its French labor force by 2,260 people. To cover
severance, early retirement and retraining costs, it made a
special 350-million franc provision.
   One problem Michelin didn't point to is finance.
Michelin's more than $1.5 billion Uniroyal Goodrich
acquisition has pushed up its already heavy debt. Net finance
charges in the first half jumped to 1.06 billion francs, more
than double the year-earlier figure.
   Michelin did warn, however, that because the acquisition
was completed in May, the impact of interest payments on its
results would be more severe in the second half.
   Michelin said in a statement that efforts to cut
production, stocks and overhead would be "pursued and
reinforced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0122
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0122.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law:
   Legal Arguments
   Focus on Contents
   Of Memo on Milken
   ----
   By Laurie P. Cohen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES (SCR)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Michael Milken is scheduled to be sentenced for his crimes
in a week and the battle over what the government may tell
the public about the former junk bond king -- and when -- is
well under way.
   A federal judge is expected to hear arguments today from
lawyers for Mr. Milken, his brother, Lowell Milken, several
media organizations and others about a sentencing memorandum
that the government has filed with the court about Mr.
Milken. The sentencing memorandum, filed under seal this
month, contains information about the six securities
fraud-related crimes to which Mr. Milken pleaded guilty in
April, as well as a host of other alleged crimes that the
government believes he committed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The government's sentencing memo, which is understood to
total more than 200 pages, is intended to persuade U.S.
District Judge Kimba Wood to issue a stiff sentence when Mr.
Milken appears before her next Monday. Mr. Milken's lawyers
have had the opportunity to rebut the government's
allegations in their own memo.
   Lawyers for Lowell Milken asked Judge Wood late Friday to
order prosecutors to delete those portions of their
sentencing memo that refer to Lowell Milken. Lowell Milken
was employed by the Beverly Hills, Calif., junk bond
department that his brother headed for Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. Drexel filed for bankruptcy this year.
   Lowell Milken had been charged with securities and tax
fraud in an indictment filed last year. But the government
agreed to dismiss all charges against Lowell Milken when his
brother agreed to plead guilty. His lawyers said that "the
government has pursued a meritless case against Lowell
Milken," and that any mention of him in his brother's
sentencing memo would violate his Fifth Amendment rights. The
Fifth Amendment of the U.S. Constitution forbids the
government from publicly charging a person with the
commission of crimes unless he has the opportunity to defend
himself at trial.
   Meanwhile, Judge Wood also will decide whether any portion
of the sentencing memo can be released prior to Mr. Milken's
sentencing. Several media organizations, including this
newspaper, have argued that the public has a right to view
the memo before Mr. Milken is sentenced. However, Mr.
Milken's attorneys oppose any release of the memo before next
week, arguing that early release could lead to "undue public
clamor and improper pressure" on the court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
