<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0112
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Arizona Public Service Makes Proposal
   For a Much Smaller Increase in Rates
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B11C
</SO>
<CO>
   PNW
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Arizona Public Service Co. proposed a sweeping settlement
with the Arizona Corporation Commission that includes a
sharply reduced rate-increase request and a $250 million cap
on liability for costs related to a three-year-old nuclear
power plant.
   Arizona's largest electric utility conditionally offered
to freeze rates for three years after raising them 9.3% next
January. The utility's pending rate increase, filed earlier
this year, calls for a 6.8% increase in each of the next
three years, or slightly more than 21% compounded.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Quite frankly we recognized that customer bills after a
21% increase would have been too high," said Mark De Michele,
president and chief executive officer. The smaller rise would
cut the increased cost to customers by $600 million over four
years, he said.
   Arizona Public Service "is moving in the right direction
by lowering its rate request," said Gary Yaquinto, director
of the commission's utilities division. He indicated,
however, that "excess capacity, operating performance,
construction imprudence" and other issues could lead to staff
recommendations of "even further cuts."
   Arizona Public Service rates were harshly criticized by
PacifiCorp during its recent attempt to acquire the Arizona
utility or its parent, Pinnacle West Capital Corp. of
Phoenix, Ariz. PacifiCorp, based in Portland, Ore., had
promised to keep rate increases to 2% a year in each of the
next four years if its takeover bid succeeded. Last month,
PacifiCorp dropped its pursuit in exchange for seasonal power
swaps with Arizona Public Service.
   "If this would have been their first {request}, there
never would have been a bid by PacifiCorp," said Edward J.
Tirello, a utility analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co. This proposal "is a quick and dirty way that cleans up"
all major disputes between the utility and state regulators.
"It makes a lot of sense."
   Mr. De Michele said the proposal wouldn't have been
possible without the PacifiCorp pact, potentially worth $260
million to Arizona Public Service. Among the proposal's
conditions are that the commission approve a $221 million
sale of the utility's 35-megawatt, coal-fired Cholla unit 4
plant. The initial PacifiCorp agreement specified that it
would buy partial interests in units 1 and 3.
   Mr. De Michele also said the lower rates were a reflection
of recently accelerated belt-tightening moves. Non-nuclear
jobs have been cut 30% to about 4,200 since 1988. About 2,840
workers are employed at the Palo Verde Nuclear Generating
Station. Capital spending budgets have been pared by $770
million over five years. Last year, the utility spent about
$270 million on capital outlays.
   The proposed $250 million write-down is related to Palo
Verde unit 3, operated and 29.1%-owned by Arizona Public
Service. The utility has been seeking to recover $1.2 billion
in plant construction costs and deferred operating expenses.
The commission, which regulates utilities, has indicated it
probably will disallow a big chunk of those costs on various
grounds, including possibly that the reactor isn't needed and
never should have been built. It began commercial operations
in Jan. 1988.
   Arizona Public Service "doesn't acknowledge that any
portion of the plant is excess capacity or should not have
been built," Mr. De Michele said. "We are proposing that the
write-off resolve all issues of imprudent expenditures."
   The proposed 9.3% rate increase includes 3.4% for new
property taxes imposed by the state legislature earlier this
year. Arizona Public Service wants commission approval for a
"pass-through mechanism" that would let the utility collect
the taxes from customers in future years without making a
rate filing. The utility also said it plans to challenge the
new taxes in court.
   Mr. Yaquinto said the commission feels "a bit stampeded"
by the utility's demand for a response to its proposal by
Oct. 31. Mr. De Michele played down the deadline. "If we're
making progress in October then we'll pursue it." If not, the
utility would ask for interim rates to be put into effect and
would pursue its pending 21% rate filing, he said. The first
hearing on that case is set for Dec. 5.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0111
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0111.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Nominee for SEC
   Supports CFTC
   On Index Futures
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMODITY FUTURES TRADING COMMISSION (CFT)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
CONGRESS (CNG)
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Richard Roberts, President Bush's nominee to
the Securities and Exchange Commission, voiced support for a
plan that would leave regulation of controversial stock-index
futures with the Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
   The plan, being floated on Capitol Hill, is an alternative
to White House-sponsored legislation that would shift index
futures to the SEC.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stock-index futures, often used in computerized
program-trading strategies, allow investors to bet on the
move of a basket of stocks without owning the actual shares.
   Mr. Roberts's stance, expressed at his confirmation
hearing before the Senate Banking Committee, is significant
because it would swing the balance on the SEC. Agency
Chairman Richard Breeden strongly favors a jurisdiction
shift, as does Commissioner Philip Lochner Jr. But Edward
Fleischman has voted against any such power transfer, and
Mary Schapiro has endorsed a third plan that would merge the
two agencies.
   The administration's plan, severely weakened by strong
opposition from the Chicago futures exchanges and Capitol
Hill Agriculture committees that oversee the CFTC, appears
dead for this legislative session. Moreover, without solid
backing from the SEC, it's unlikely Congress will press ahead
with the plan and might focus exclusively on a compromise
next year.
   At the hearing, Mr. Roberts also offered support for
another tenet of the Capitol Hill alternative -- a provision
to shift the regulation of margins on stock-index futures to
the Federal Reserve Board. Margins -- the good-faith money
needed to trade the futures -- currently are set by the
exchanges, with the CFTC allowed to intervene only in
specifically defined emergencies. A similar switch is
included in the administration's proposal.
   Mr. Roberts also told the senators that he "intends to
improve communications with the CFTC" and create a "better
spirit of cooperation" between the futures agency and the
SEC.
   The committee is expected to approve his nomination this
week, after which he isn't likely to have any difficulty
passing the full Senate. Mr. Roberts, 39 years old, is a
former top staffer for Sen. Richard Shelby (D., Ala.), a
Banking Committee member who was one of only two senators to
quiz Mr. Roberts at the hearing. The questioning was friendly
and generally supportive of the conservative Democrat from
both Sen. Shelby and committee Chairman Donald Riegle (D.,
Mich.).
   Mr. Roberts wondered whether the SEC was doing enough to
confront "front-running," which frequently involves trading
in futures or stocks in front of a large order in the other
market. He said he is concerned that the SEC isn't generating
many of its own cases, instead relying on the exchanges to
provide referrals. The SEC hasn't been able to bring
front-running cases, and the agency contends that's because
it can track only the stock side of the transaction and not
the futures side.
   Mr. Roberts focused largely on Wall Street-related
problems in his testimony. Asked what his biggest enforcement
priorities were, the nominee said they were "rooting out
insider trading, stopping penny-stock fraud" and slowing
fraudulent investment advisers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0110
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0110.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Soviet Union's Chief Accountant Wants
   To Set Up Group Resembling U.S. CPAs
   ----
   By Robin Goldwyn Blumenthal
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B11H
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
ACCOUNTING (ACC)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The Soviet Union's chief accountant expects to
issue new standards for all enterprises by June, and he wants
to set up a professional group resembling the American
Institute of Certified Public Accountants.
   At a meeting organized by Ernst &amp; Young here, Nicholai
Panteleev, chief accountant for the Soviet Ministry of
Finance, also said that by early next year he hopes to make
some other rules changes regarding accounting for joint
ventures. Mr. Panteleev heads the accounting rule-making body
in the Soviet Union.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the most part, Soviet accounting is predicated on a
centralized form of government. The Soviet accounting system
"now resembles an army code," Mr. Panteleev said. He said he
would like to make the system "more democratic," and he wants
to pass some of the functions that the government handles to
an outside group.
   With the current system, "if it directs to turn right, one
can't possibly turn left," he said. The current accounting
model was designed "strictly to forward the plans and
direction of the government," Mr. Panteleev said. Current
standards "are largely used for economic statistics as
opposed to financial reporting," said James Searing, national
director of Ernst &amp; Young's international business services.
   The government only recently allowed joint ventures to
record revenue on an accrual rather than a cash basis. In the
past, an enterprise would have to actually receive a cash
payment before it could record a sale. Although Mr. Panteleev
didn't specify what the joint-venture changes might be, one
might be to also move expense accounting to accrual from a
cash basis.
   Mr. Panteleev said his goal is to bring Soviet accounting
rules closer to internationally accepted standards. But it is
difficult to envision a Soviet accounting system until
questions about how a free-market economy will work are
answered. And those questions, Mr. Panteleev said, are best
left to the politicians.
   Mr. Panteleev said the biggest challenge seems to be to
establish a system of auditing and review, such as the one
that operates in the U.S. The concept of auditing didn't
exist in the Soviet Union until recently.
   "Under new market conditions, there will be a great
necessity to have an independent body to exercise control,"
Mr. Panteleev said. "The issue of accounting management is
connected directly with the issue of any market standard," he
said.
   Mr. Panteleev visited the Securities and Exchange
Commission and apparently was impressed. The SEC has
statutory authority to establish accounting and reporting
standards for public companies, though it has largely left
that role to the private sector. The SEC also enforces the
rules.
   Mr. Panteleev said he would like to create a private
organization similar to the AICPA for licensing. But he
didn't say when that might happen.
   Other issues involve developing standards that are more
similar to those the rest of the world uses. A task force of
the United Nations Centre on Transnational Corporations has
been advising the Soviet Union on how to accomplish this
goal, and it has provided expertise on international
accounting standards.
   Mr. Panteleev also sees re-educating professionals as a
major goal. The Soviet Union has about two million
bookkeepers and about 300,000 in-house chief accountants.
"They have to move from a bookkeeping culture to an
accounting profession," said Mr. Searing of Ernst &amp; Young.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0109
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0109.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   World Wire
   ----
   Compiled by William Mathewson
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST EUROP NSANY TOYOY F.RNA G.VOW FORGN TAXES LATAM
LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AIRLINES (AIR)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   BREAKING BRITAIN'S SPEED LIMIT
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Two Japanese car makers and one from France reportedly
have been warned not to glamorize speed and high performance
in advertising and selling their models in Britain.
   According to a Japanese news agency, Britain's Advertising
Standards Authority has criticized Nissan Motor Co. and
Toyota Motor Corp., along with the French manufacturer
Renault S.A., for emphasizing the ability of their cars to
reach speeds of 155 miles an hour. This is more than twice
the 70 mph speed limit that applies on all British motorways.
   A spokesman for the authority was quoted by the news
agency as saying that ads stressing speed and glamorizing
power appeared to have come back in fashion after being
dropped some years ago. "We will be keeping a very close eye
on car advertisements in future," the spokesman reportedly
added.
   An official of the Royal Society for the Prevention of
Accidents, noting that there was ample evidence that speed
was a major factor in traffic fatalities, said: "We are very
pleased the authority is getting tough with emotional
language in car adverts which leads to aggressive driving."
                                                                                                       

   A LOAN FOR SHANGHAI VOLKSWAGEN
                                                                                                       

   Shanghai Volkswagen reportedly signed an agreement with
China's Bank of Industry &amp; Commerce to borrow 128 million
yuan (about $27 million) to be used for Chinese-made parts.
Shanghai's Liberation Daily said the loan also would serve as
a "shot in the arm," enabling Shanghai VW to complete its
1990 production plan. The report called Shanghai VW the "pet
of the Shanghai financial community." Shanghai VW is a joint
venture of Shanghai Automobile &amp; Tractor Industries and
Volkswagen AG.
                                                                                                       

   HELPING NORTHERN IRELAND
                                                                                                       

   The European Community said it would give 35 million
European currency units ($45.9 million) to projects in
Northern Ireland. The money is being targeted for
infrastructure projects as well as various social programs
trying to reconcile the province's Roman Catholic and
Protestant communities. The EC commissioner for regional
policy, Bruce Millan, said: "The (EC) itself was born out of
the need to resolve conflict and achieve reconciliation, and
it is appropriate that it should today seek to help Northern
Ireland in the same way."
                                                                                                       

   GATT DOORS SHUT ON CHINA
                                                                                                       

   A Beijing delegation failed in its latest attempt to gain
China's entry into the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade, the global trading organization. China, which has
observer status in the GATT and has been trying to gain
membership for some eight years, has been told that it has to
open up its markets more to foreign trade and reduce tariffs
before it can be considered. Beijing's bid for recognition
also was set back considerably by last year's Tiananmen
Square killings.
                                                                                                       

   MORE PRIVATIZING IN PORTUGAL
                                                                                                       

   The Portuguese government will sell its minority holdings
in 34 companies, the news agency Lusa reported. The assets,
in each case less than 10% of a company, are to be sold
through direct negotiation with potential buyers, a Finance
Ministry spokesman said; current shareholders may be granted
preferential rights. The companies involved run the gamut
from beer maker Companhia de Cervejas Estrela S.A. to the
national zoo.
                                                                                                       

   LINKING SEOUL AND BELGRADE
                                                                                                       

   Yugoslavia and South Korea will establish the first-ever
air link between the two countries, a Yugoslav news agency
reported. Yugoslav Airlines plans to open a direct link
between Belgrade and Seoul by the end of this year, and
Korean Air is expected to fly to Belgrade soon thereafter,
the report said.
                                                                                                       

   THE FUTURE OF EUROPE'S ELDERLY
                                                                                                       

   Europe's old people may have to go back to work, reversing
the current trend toward early retirement, as families shrink
and a labor shortfall looms, according to papers discussed at
a recent Council of Europe workshop.
   And as a trend toward very small families continues, the
many over-65s expected by the year 2025 -- more than 20% in
Sweden, West Germany and the Netherlands against half that
figure now -- will likely experience increasing social
isolation due to the absence of family ties.
   "The picture isn't all black," said Italian demographer
Raimondo Cagiano Azevedo. "The gray revolution is the result
of medical improvements and a change in life styles, such as
women joining the labor force. . . . But there will be
problems if governments fail to adopt a long-term strategy."
   Like other demographers at the seminar, Mr. Azevedo urged
a quick overhaul of national welfare systems to cater to
growing numbers of the "old old" -- those over 75 years. By
2025, they are expected to account for 8% of people in
Britain, France and Switzerland.
                                                                                                       

   POSTSCRIPT . . .
                                                                                                       

   In the first six months of this year, China confiscated
195 pounds of opium, an amount 17 times greater than in the
same period last year.
</TEXT>
