<HL>
   Index Technology
   To Unveil Software
   For Mainframes
   ----
   By William M. Bulkeley
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B11E
</SO>
<CO>
   INDX
</CO>
<IN>
SOFTWARE (SOF)
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Index Technology Corp. will introduce
tomorrow a product to help corporate software experts update
old mainframe software programs, Richard Carpenter, chairman
and chief executive officer, said.
   The product, XL/Recover, marks a move into a new area of
the software-engineering field that Index helped pioneer. It
will be available next week. Index, the nation's biggest
maker of products for the computer-aided software-engineering
market, known as CASE, has previously made software tools to
improve the productivity of programmers writing new programs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In an interview, Mr. Carpenter said the XL/Recover
software program, which will sell for $9,800 and runs on
IBM-compatible personal computers, "is a major thrust in our
offerings for 1991." He declined to predict sales but said it
will "probably account for 10% to 25% of revenue" in the
future.
   Last year, Index earned $2.3 million, or 50 cents a share,
on revenue of $38 million. During this year, Index has
continued to grow rapidly, but earnings have declined.
First-half net was $961,000, or 20 cents a share, down 21%
from $1.2 million, or 27 cents a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose 39% to $24.4 million from $17.5 million.
   Mr. Carpenter declined to predict earnings for the current
quarter or the rest of the year. "This is continuing to be an
investment year for Index. The good thing is we're beginning
to get the results of all that investment into the
marketplace," he said.
   The company's new product addresses what should be a
substantial market, Mr. Carpenter said. He added that in most
companies, 60% to 80% of the software-development budget is
spent adjusting old software programs to address new business
conditions rather than designing new programs. For example,
when a company eliminates a layer of bureaucracy in the
credit-approval department, software has to be rewritten to
make sure that bills don't still require approvals from those
job titles.
   XL/Recovery helps systems analysts look at the old COBOL
software code that runs on most companies' mainframe
computers. It can read the code, determine the logic and
business rules used in the application, and draw charts of
the structure of the code, making it easy for programmers to
see how changing one part of the program will affect other
parts.
   Several other companies, including Cambridge-based Bachman
Information Systems Inc., already make programs that
automatically turn old COBOL "spaghetti code" that is
extremely complex and hard for humans to follow into
better-organized code. But Index said XL/Recovery goes beyond
that by capturing information about both the data involved
and the process by which it is manipulated.
   John Dunkle, an analyst with WorkGroup Technologies Inc.,
Hampton, N.H., said, "Other CASE vendors are talking about
this capability, but nobody is delivering it yet." He added
that for Index to pioneer the technology is surprising
because "usually the largest companies in any market are
somewhat sluggish. The small companies usually tend to
introduce technologies faster."
   Mr. Carpenter said the company plans a major publicity
campaign starting tomorrow. He said: "We're very eager to see
how folks respond to it. We have to wait to see the market
reception." He added that Index plans several other
significant product announcements later this year, but he
declined to comment on the products involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0096
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0096.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   OPEC's Output
   May Forestall
   Energy Shortfall
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Authoritative new estimates show that members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries are pumping
enough oil to forestall -- at least until winter --
world-wide energy shortages because of the Middle East
crisis.
   However, rising prices are building political pressures to
tap stockpiles such as the U.S. Strategic Petroleum Reserve
even though these were established as buffers against
physical shortages, not volatile markets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Total OPEC output has rebounded from the August low of
19.7 million barrels a day to 22 million barrels a day or
more for September. That level generally hadn't been expected
until October.
   The extra oil is coming mainly from Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates and Venezuela. It's enough to replace
three-fourths of the four million barrels a day of embargoed
Iraqi and Kuwaiti oil.
   Demand for OPEC's oil still is higher than its output,
partly as a result of panic buying. But rising flow rates
combined with high world inventories make it unlikely that
the International Energy Agency's emergency oil-sharing
mechanism will be triggered when the governing board of 21
oil-consuming nations meets again in Paris Friday.
   The increased output doesn't bar individual nations from
dipping into their strategic oil reserves to alleviate high
prices. Nor does it completely rule out a possible supply
crunch later this year. "It's going to be a touch-and-go
winter," said Thomas A. Petrie of Petrie Parkman &amp; Co., a
Denver investment firm specializing in energy. "We could
still see some pretty tight conditions in November and
December in some fuels."
   It's true that supplies of some petroleum products --
including kerosene, jet fuel and naphtha, a petrochemical
feedstock -- already are tight in some areas, particularly in
regions of the Persian Gulf and Asia. "This reflects the loss
of Kuwait refining capacity and the added demands associated
with the military buildup in the Gulf," Cambridge Energy
Research Associates reported Friday.
   But crude oil supplies are ample everywhere even though
some refiners worry that some oil replacing the lost Iraqi
petroleum is of lower quality. In the U.S., according to the
latest count by the Department of Energy, crude oil
inventories total 373.1 million barrels, 35 million above the
year-earlier level. And in Europe, according to Energy
Security Analysis Inc., crude oil inventories are 25 million
barrels higher than they were a year ago.
   Energy Security Analysis is a Washington-based firm that
monitors oil supplies world-wide. It estimates that at the
end of August commercial onshore inventories of crude oil and
chief petroleum products totaled 2.93 billion barrels. That
was 87 million barrels above the year-earlier level. If
government stockpiles are included, total global inventories
were 113 million barrels higher than a year ago.
   "We've seen no statistical evidence that inventories are
being drawn down significantly," said Sarah Emerson, a vice
president of Energy Security Analysis. Still, she said, the
surplus is getting smaller just as demand increases
seasonally. "No one is going to run out of crude," she said,
"but in a month or two we could start having problems on
products."
   Oil markets appear to be expecting severe disruptions of
supplies. Petroleum prices underscore that sentiment. They
continued their run-up last week, reaching a nine-year high
of more than $35 a barrel.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the futures price of
crude oil for November delivery settled Friday at $35.43 a
barrel -- up $2.01 a barrel for the day and $4.27 a barrel
for the week. Gasoline and heating oil futures also continued
to show sizzling gains, each advancing toward $1 a gallon.
   U.S. and European energy officials foresee some problems
in the distribution of petroleum products, as is happening
already in Asia. Still, many are concerned that the potential
for a supply crunch exists, even if war doesn't break out in
the Middle East, because the global systems to produce,
transport and refine oil have grown taut in the wake of the
Persian Gulf standoff over Iraqi-occupied Kuwait."We are
operating in a fragile environment," one official explained.
"At every level, from the wellhead through the refinery, we
are at capacity."
   Still, energy representatives of oil-consuming nations
have been pleasantly surprised at the rapid increases in
production by Saudi Arabia and others. According to most
estimates, the kingdom already is producing the additional
two million barrels a day it had pledged, putting its current
output at between 7.3 million and 7.5 million barrels. And it
is understood to be pushing to expand its output to eight or
8.5 million barrels a day.
   Actual "supplies" from OPEC -- exports of oil plus the
volumes refined and used domestically -- exceed production at
the moment. That's because Saudi Arabia and others are
selling oil from storage as well as from current production.
Petro-Logistics Ltd. of Geneva monitors both the volumes
refined and exported by OPEC and estimates that such supplies
currently total 22.2 million barrels a day.
   But surveys of oil in tankers at sea by Petro-Logistics
indicate that so-called producer-owned stocks afloat are
beginning to shrink.
   Further evidence of the declines in oil at sea comes from
tanker charterings, which dropped sharply in recent weeks.
However, according to Robert Boslego, a Winchester, Mass.,
oil consultant who monitors such charterings, there has been
"a significant rebound in tanker chartering fixtures since
the depths reached in August."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0095
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0095.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Brazil's Chief to Reach Out
   To World in U.N. Address
   ----
   By Thomas Kamm
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRASILIA, Brazil -- When Fernando Collor de Mello
addresses the United Nations General Assembly today, he'll be
saying a lot of new things for a Brazilian president.
   The leader of a country denounced internationally for
environmental destruction will emphasize his concern for the
ecology. The president of a nation long viewed as one of the
world's most protectionist will talk of free markets and
economic liberalization. Denounced recently in an Amnesty
International report as a country where extermination squads
run rampant, Brazil will stress human rights. And viewed
suspiciously as a country trying to build an atomic bomb and
help such countries as Iraq and Libya enhance their military
potential, Brazil now affirms its commitment to peaceful use
of nuclear energy and disarmament.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The message I will bring to the U.S. is that there's a
profound economic and cultural revolution going on in
Brazil," Mr. Collor said Friday in an interview on the eve of
his departure for a week-long visit to the U.S. "We are
establishing the conditions for the free market to operate.
We are preparing seriously to enter the First World."
   Brazil still has a ways to go. Its monthly inflation rate
of about 13% is still more than twice that of major
industrialized countries, income distribution is among the
most unfair in the world and many here complain that their
economic situation is getting worse, not better.
   But many Brazilians also agree that the country is
undergoing a sea change six months after Mr. Collor took
office, although he is sometimes criticized as authoritarian
and even if there are often more words and publicity stunts
than concrete results. In the latest sign of his government's
no-nonsense attitude, Brazil Thursday ordered the closing and
liquidation of four state banks and four official lending
agencies for "serious irregularities."
   Sitting ramrod-straight behind his desk throughout the
interview, the 41-year-old Mr. Collor, his hair flecked with
gray, made the following points:
   -- Brazil will resist pressure to make a token foreign
debt payment as it prepares to resume negotiations with
creditors, but the country hopes to sign an accord it can
comply with to avoid new debt payment suspensions in the
future.
   -- The Persian Gulf crisis "creates difficulties" for his
bold anti-inflation plan that will need to be solved
"creatively," with cooperation among the government, unions
and employers to prevent excessive wage and price increases.
   -- Mr. Collor welcomed President George Bush's "Initiative
for the Americas" as consistent with plans for greater South
American economic integration and said he hoped to give it
"practical content as soon as possible."
   -- He said Brazil's controversial nuclear program is
undergoing a "profound re-evaluation" to reorient it toward
peaceful uses and said this should be done under the control
of society rather than under a "veil of secrecy."
   He affirmed his government's commitment to the "fight" to
save the Amazon rain forest and called for more international
cooperation in ecological matters.
   Regarding the sweeping anti-inflation plan he enforced
when he took office, which included an 18-month freeze on
almost half the money circulating in the Brazilian economy,
Mr. Collor said the drop in the monthly inflation rate to 13%
from 84% largely without price controls is "already a great
victory" but "much remains to be done."
   Acknowledging that the plan has aggravated Brazil's
already "shameful" income distribution, Mr. Collor said the
adjustment plan isn't an end in itself but aims to give the
state the means to meet Brazil's pressing housing,
educational and health needs and reduce social inequalities.
   He appealed to Brazilian society to help him attain this
aim by entering into a "national understanding," a sort of
pact that would, among other things, prevent "wild
capitalists" from making excessive profits through price
mark-ups and "radical unionists" from pushing for
wage-and-price indexation. Discussions on this pact are to
begin this week.
   As Brazil, the developing world's largest debtor, readies
itself to negotiate with its creditors next month -- an
essential step to obtain a recently approved $2 billion
standby loan from the International Monetary Fund -- Mr.
Collor and debt negotiator Jorio Dauster, in a separate
interview, said Brazil's payments capacity was linked to its
future economic growth.
   "The question isn't how much the country can grow after
paying its debt, but how much we can pay after guaranteeing
our economic growth," Mr. Collor said.
   Pressed by creditors to make a token payment on some of
the approximately $10 billion in arrears Brazil has
accumulated since it suspended interest and capital payments
on most of its $114 billion foreign debt last year, Brazilian
officials urged bankers to take a long-term view.
   Comparing Brazil to a company whose shareholders have
ousted the old management and replaced it with a new team
that's cleaning up the mess, Mr. Collor said "one can't
require that this company pay such a sum as to impede the
success" of this cleaning-up process. Added Mr. Dauster: "Our
payments capacity is a dynamic concept: as we start to grow,
it will become much bigger."
   Bankers and diplomats retort, however, that Brazil also
has to take a long-term view and will have to quickly
normalize relations with the international financial
community if it wants to obtain foreign financing to help it
grow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
