<HL>
   Ford Canada Workers Ratify Contract
   Providing Gains in Wages and Benefits
   ----
   By Lynne Kilpatrick
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   FC T.FMC LABOR C GM F
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Striking workers at Ford Motor Co.'s Canadian
subsidiary yesterday voted overwhelmingly in favor of a
generous wage and benefit package that the Canadian unit of
cash-strapped Chrysler Corp. may find difficult to match.
   The agreement, reached after a marathon bargaining session
Friday, met the Canadian Auto Workers' major demands. The
12,800 Ford Motor Co. of Canada workers were expected to
return to work this morning, ending the week-long strike.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The agreement includes percentage wage increases in each
year of the three-year contract, improved cost-of-living
protection, added time off and a broad income-security
program.
   Wages will increase by 7.5% in the first year, 6.7% in the
second year and 4.8% in the third. The increases include
estimated cost-of-living allowances of 4.5%, 4.7% and 2.8%,
respectively, designed to provide 90% protection against
inflation.
   Ford Canada also has established a 100 million Canadian
dollar (US$86.6 million) fund to finance the generous early
retirement, severance pay and income supplement programs
agreed to in the contract.
   Union President Robert White called the agreement "the
best worker income-security program" in the industry and said
he expects it to become a model for labor negotiations in
other industries.
   The agreement will be the basis for negotiations with the
Canadian unit of General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Canada
Ltd. The auto workers' contracts with the Canadian units of
the Big Three auto makers expired Sept. 14. Ford Canada was
the Canadian Auto Worker's target in the pattern-setting
negotiations.
   Mr. White said GM Canada probably will be the next company
the union negotiates with. Nick Hall, a GM Canada spokesman,
said the Ford contract looks expensive, but he declined to
elaborate.
   Chrysler Canada officials declined to comment on the Ford
Canada contract, but analysts said the cash-strapped company
would have difficulty affording such a settlement.
   Chrysler is financially "very weak and there are questions
of whether it could even withstand a strike," Toronto auto
analyst Dennis DesRosiers said earlier in the Ford
negotiations.
   In separate U.S. auto talks, Chrysler already has warned
that it may not be able to match the settlement the United
Auto Workers reached last week with General Motors.
   Ford Canada's chief negotiator, Donald McKenzie, declined
to say how much the agreement will cost the company, but
called it "a handsome settlement" as far as workers are
concerned.
   The contract requires that Ford provide one-year's notice
in the event of a plant closing and six months' notice of job
losses due to technological change or outsourcing -- the
buying of products from outside sources, rather than
producing them inhouse.
   When jobs are lost for these reasons, the contract
provides for early retirement at full pension for older
workers with at least 10 years of service. Depending on
length of service, laid-off workers also may receive 95% of
their income for up to three years, or choose severance
payments of up to C$65,000.
   The union said the compensation plan is designed to
encourage older workers to leave the work force ahead of
younger ones.
   Also in the new settlement is an annual C$500 vacation
bonus for workers, and workers will also get three additional
four-day weekends a year. Mr. White said the extra time off,
a key issue in the talks, is likely to have an influence on
the auto talks in the U.S.
   Ford Canada also agreed to create a "social justice fund"
to make contributions to such things as international
development and relief projects and food banks. The company
will contribute one cent per hour worked to the fund, up to
C$250,000. It will also contribute to the Canadian Auto
Workers' child care program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0081
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0081.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Stuart Hall Co. Says
   Profit Increased 50%
   In Fiscal 3rd Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B11C
</SO>
<CO>
   STUH
</CO>
<IN>
RAW AND FINISHED PAPER PRODUCTS (PAP)
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Stuart Hall Co.'s growing distribution
base and "an exceptionally good" back-to-school season
contributed to a boost in earnings for the fiscal third
quarter, ended Aug. 31, Charles G. Hanson, chairman and chief
executive officer, said.
   Mr. Hanson said net income for the office- and
school-products company was "50% over last year's"
third-quarter earnings of $544,000, or 14 cents a share. But
the comparison benefits from a $188,000 net charge, from
inventory write-down, that substantially trimmed year-earlier
results. The 1989 quarter also was hurt by an unusually large
$289,379 pretax bad-debt provision.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Per-share figures reflect a 4-for-3 stock split paid in
December 1989.
   Total sales for the quarter are expected to be $40.4
million, a 28% increase from $31.6 million for the
year-earlier period. Mr. Hanson said he expects continued
earnings growth of 30% to 40% next year.
   "We are adding constantly to our distribution base. We
estimate that some 46,000 outlets now carry a pretty broad
base of our product," Mr. Hanson said in an interview.
   Upgraded office-supply products, which he called "the
backbone" of Stuart Hall's office product lines, also added
to increased sales, but earnings growth was stunted
nonetheless by the effects of a "depressed pricing structure
throughout the industry," Mr. Hanson said.
   "This year was probably the worst for pricing structure
that I can recall," he said. "Had it not been for that we
would have done substantially better."
   Mr. Hanson said he expects to benefit from some "very fine
equipment" purchased from a German-based paper-supply company
that closed its American operation. The equipment purchased
from Herlitz Co. will be placed in Stuart Hall's Kansas City
headquarters, its Bessemer, Ala., facility, and in a new
Woodland, Calif., facility scheduled to open in December, he
said.
   Mr. Hanson said the company will release within the next
30 to 45 days a new line of about 50 products made from 100%
recycled paper products.
   People are "caught up in the recycling movement but are
not willing to pay more for a recycled sheet of paper," he
said. "We are delighted" with the new recycled product, he
added, because "the consumer will have an opportunity to buy
a 100% recycled product at the same price he's spending for
the product now."
   Mr. Hanson wouldn't project how much the new products
might affect earnings, but he said "it will have a favorable
impact on our bottom line. It will be a major introduction,
the largest thing that's happened to us in 1990."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900924-0080
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900924-0080.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Analysts' Profit Estimates Grow Gloomier
   ----
   By Craig Torres
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   MRC SNS CBL HTK LAB PA HLT D AEP PEG PPW KMB SPP GE JPM
BAC BT MHC CCI
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Analysts, glimpsing how even the first shock
waves from surging oil prices are souring consumer sentiment
and crimping spending, are forging new corporate earnings
estimates -- this time with a recession in mind.
   Since Aug. 15, 75% of all revisions on estimated 1991
earnings have been decreases, according to Zacks Investment
Research, Chicago, which tracks some 4,000 companies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This is the worst set of readings since the last
recession in 1981," says Benjamin Zacks, executive vice
president of the company. "These numbers are getting very,
very bleak."
   And so are the market's reactions. Even minor adjustments
in earnings forecasts are triggering torrents of sell orders.
On Friday, for example, Scott Paper fell 17% after company
executives told investors that third-quarter and full-year
profit may fall below year-earlier results.
   Analysts have even reversed their optimism in formerly
bullish groups as recessionary trends become more apparent.
From June 15 through Aug. 15, analysts raised 27 estimates on
semiconductor companies and lowered 11, Mr. Zacks says. But
in the past month, only five estimates were raised while 25
were lowered.
   Reinforcing the "safe growth" theme, estimate revisions
have gone up for hospital management companies, such as
Humana, U.S. HealthCare and United Healthcare, Mr. Zacks
says, as well as for drug makers and mining concerns. And in
general, big makers of nondurable goods for consumers with
dependable earnings growth, such as Warner-Lambert, Philip
Morris, Johnson &amp; Johnson and Procter &amp; Gamble "are holding
to slight earnings upgrades," Mr. Zacks adds.
   Those are the few stocks that investors are holding onto
as they run for cover, shares of companies in which they
retain any confidence that profit projections will be
fulfilled. Stocks that aren't as well known by investors and
aren't as closely followed by Wall Street analysts are being
hammered hard as safety-first investors dump them.
   This pattern shows up in the market barometers. So far
this year, on a total return basis, which includes both price
change and reinvested dividends, the Dow Jones Industrial
Average is down 6.16%, and Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index
is off 9.61%. But the rest of the market, as measured by the
Wilshire 5000 index minus the 500 S&amp;P stocks, has sunk
16.51%.
   This isn't to say big brand-name stocks are escaping
unscathed from this round of second-guessing earnings
strength. This month, through last Thursday, the S&amp;P 500 has
fared a bit worse than the remaining stocks in the Wilshire
5000: On a total return basis the S&amp;P 500 fell 3.24%,
compared with a 3.07% decline in the Wilshire remainder.
   "You have total capitulation -- no tolerance to own stocks
with a question regarding the fundamentals," says James Awad,
president of BMI Capital Corp., a money management company.
This shooting down of stock by stock has occurred on such a
scale that the overall damage "is as bad as if there had been
an aggregate cleanout in the market, as in October 1987," he
says.
   Even the year's all-stars aren't being spared from the
rash of earnings revisions.
   Claire's Stores shares, which gained more than 34% in the
second quarter, dropped 25% last week. On Wednesday, Alex.
Brown &amp; Sons analyst Chris Vroom trimmed his profit estimate
for the women's specialty retailer's current fiscal year by
no more than 10 cents a share to $1.20.
   Sell-offs in stocks such as Scott Paper means money is
shifting from those shares to either "safe growth" issues or
out of the stock market altogether.
   But even the big blue chips may not withstand selling
pressures in coming days, says Stefan Abrams, chief
investment strategist at Kidder Peabody. Investors already
are selling stocks of companies with earnings prospects that
are relatively invulnerable to economic troubles, he says.
   "You can see it in top tier growth issues -- Coke, Pepsi,
and hospital and drug stocks," Mr. Abrams says, asserting
that the market is "in the early stages of capitulation."
   Robert Stovall, president of Stovall/Twenty-First
Advisers, observes that hoarding blue chips is typical
behavior early in a bear market. But if a sell-off
accelerates to stampede proportions, the big, easily traded
shares are the ones investors are likely to sell first.
   Mr. Abrams of Kidder says the S&amp;P 500 is about 12% above
"fair value," which is based on the yield of the one-year
Treasury bill. "The first reasonable expectation of a
stopping point in the current decline is fair value," he
says. That would be roughly 273 on the S&amp;P 500, which closed
Friday at 311.32, down 0.16; a comparable decline in the
industrial average would bring the average to 2210.89 from
Friday's finish at 2512.38, down 5.94. "The greatest
vulnerability will be in the most liquid stocks -- what
people sell in a capitulation phase," he says.
   What could precipitate such a sell-off? "It could be event
driven -- such as an outbreak of war. It could be the
continuing sand-papering of the investment community by a
crude oil price that keeps edging up," Mr. Abrams says.
   Whatever happens, Mr. Abrams advises investors to sell
stocks of any company with "questionable" profit prospects
and hang on to cash, perhaps investing in "a short-term
instrument of impeccable quality."
   He adds: "It is no time to go foraging around for a few
extra percentage points of yield."
   ---
   Friday's Market Activity
                                                                                                       

   The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 5.94 to 2512.38
because of rising oil prices, declining hopes for a quick
budget accord in Washington, and bad news in the banking
industry. The loss for the week was 51.73, or 2%.
   Friday's loss would have been greater, were it not for
program buying related to the "triple-witching" expirations
of September stock-index futures and options, and options on
individual stocks.
   Program activity also was responsible for pushing volume
to 201,050,000 shares on the New York Stock Exchange, the
busiest since Aug. 23 when the industrial average hit its low
for the year. Average volume the previous four days last week
was 136.1 million shares.
   Iraq's expulsion of diplomats from the U.S., Egypt and
several other countries helped boost November crude-oil
futures contracts $2.01 a barrel to $35.43. That price jump
hurt stocks, as did the news that the chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee would seek a postponement of
automatic budget cuts, which take effect next week if no
deficit-cutting budget accord is reached by then.
   Also weighing on the market was a broad sell-off in bank
stocks in the wake of Chase Manhattan announcing sweeping
restructuring moves. Shares of Chase fell 1 to 12 3/4 on Big
Board volume of 2.6 million shares. The company set a
third-quarter restructuring charge at $350 million and a
loan-loss provision at $650 million, and said it plans to cut
the dividend to 30 cents a share from 62 cents.
   Among other money-center bank issues: Citicorp dropped 7/8
to 15 3/4; Manufacturers Hanover tumbled 2 7/8 to 23; Bankers
Trust New York fell 1 3/4 to 34 1/4; BankAmerica slid 1/2 to
20 1/4, and J.P. Morgan fell 3/4 to 32 1/8.
   But General Electric, which had lost 9% earlier this week
amid concerns about possible problems at its
financial-services unit, gained 3/4 to 55 7/8. While some
critics say the company's profit growth will slow because of
the prospects for the unit, GE Capital, this newspaper
reported that analysts remain positive on the stock.
   Scott Paper plunged 6 7/8 to 34 3/8 after the company said
operating earnings for the third quarter and full year could
fall short of year-earlier levels. Shares of Kimberly-Clark,
a competitor in the paper-products business, fell 2 1/8 to 72
3/4.
   Four utility issues that Smith Barney, Harris Upham cited
as havens amid the market's current jitters moved higher.
PacifiCorp rose 7/8 to 19 1/2; Public Service Enterprise
Group added 1/2 to 23 1/4; American Electric Power rose 3/8
to 26 1/2, and Dominion Resources gained 1/4 to 42 7/8.
   Hilton Hotels advanced 7/8 to 30 1/4. The company said it
plans to buy back six million common shares, or about 12.5%
of its shares outstanding.
   Primerica added 1/8 to 20 3/4. The company's board
approved the buy-back of as many as three million common
shares.
   Milton Roy jumped 3 3/4 to 26 3/4 after reaching a
definitive merger agreement with Sundstrand, which is
offering $28 a share for the company. Corroon &amp; Black dropped
1 5/8 to 29 1/4.
   Aon withdrew its $40-a-share takeover bid for the company,
which had rejected the offer in favor of pursuing a
stock-swap merger with Britain's Willis Faber.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index fell 1.17
to 316.01, extending its loss for the week to 1.7%.
   Howtek fell 3/4 to 7 1/2. Business Week magazine reported
Dean Witter Reynolds, which controls about 20% of the
company, is battling short sellers that collectively own more
than one million shares, or a 13% stake.
   Shares of Nichols Institute, which estimated that
third-quarter earnings could be 10% below analysts' highest
forecasts, tumbled 1 7/8 to 12 3/4.
   ---
