<HL>
   Business Brief -- Security Pacific Corp.:
   Firm Acquires Some Assets,
   Liabilities of Failed Thrift
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   SPC
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
WESTERN U.S. BANKS (BAW)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   Security Pacific Corp. said it paid $44.4 million to
assume certain assets and liabilities of Mercury Federal
Savings &amp; Loan Association, the Huntington Beach, Calif.,
thrift that was seized by the federal Resolution Trust Corp.
last February.
   Los Angeles-based Security Pacific said it is acquiring
$1.4 billion in total deposits, including $1.3 billion in
core deposits. It is also assuming $340 million in loans from
the thrift, most of them residential loans.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The purchase price, which is slightly more than 3% of core
deposits, appears to be at the lower end of what banks have
been paying for core deposits of failed thrifts in recent
months.
   Mercury Federal had total assets of $1.7 billion and total
liabilities of $1.8 billion, as of July 31.
   Security Pacific is the parent company of Security Pacific
National Bank.
</TEXT>
