<HL>
   Business Brief -- Boston Edison Co.:
   Court Reverses Judgment
   Towns Won From Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
09/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BSE
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Boston Edison Co. said the U.S. Court of Appeals in Boston
reversed a $39.3 million antitrust judgment against the
company.
   The company last year was ordered to pay the damages to
the towns of Concord and Wellesley, Mass., after a jury found
that wholesale rates the utility charged the towns violated
antitrust laws. The towns alleged price discrimination,
anticompetitive restrictions and price squeezing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The appeals court, however, noting that the towns could
have purchased power from other suppliers, said the towns
failed to prove that Boston Edison had a monopoly.
   Boston Edison said that the 1989 judgment hadn't been
reflected in the company's financial statements, and thus the
appeals court decision won't affect the company's earnings.
</TEXT>
